  <div class="container">
    <section id="intro">
      <h2 class="section-title">What is Computer Networking?</h2>
      <p class="intro-text">
        Computer networking is how devices communicate with each other, enabling everything from browsing websites to sending emails. 
        Whether you're just starting out or looking to deepen your knowledge, this guide will help you understand the fundamentals 
        and provide resources to master networking concepts.
      </p>
      
      
    </section>
  
    <section id="fundamentals">
      <h2 class="section-title">Networking Fundamentals</h2>
      <p class="intro-text">
        Before diving into complex topics, it's essential to understand the basic building blocks of networking.
        These fundamental concepts form the foundation for everything else in networking.
      </p>
      
      <div class="tech-grid">
        <div class="tech-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-layer-group"></i> OSI Model</h3>
          <p>
            The OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) model divides network communication into 7 layers, each with specific functions:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Layer 7: Application</strong> - User interfaces and data (HTTP, SMTP)</li>
            <li><strong>Layer 6: Presentation</strong> - Data translation and encryption</li>
            <li><strong>Layer 5: Session</strong> - Connection management between devices</li>
            <li><strong>Layer 4: Transport</strong> - End-to-end connections (TCP, UDP)</li>
            <li><strong>Layer 3: Network</strong> - Routing and logical addressing (IP)</li>
            <li><strong>Layer 2: Data Link</strong> - Physical addressing (MAC)</li>
            <li><strong>Layer 1: Physical</strong> - Cables, signals, and hardware</li>
          </ul>
          <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/learning/ddos/glossary/open-systems-interconnection-model-osi/" class="learn-btn" target="_blank">Learn More</a>
        </div>
        
        <div class="tech-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-exchange-alt"></i> TCP/IP Model</h3>
          <p>
            The TCP/IP model is a simplified, practical version of the OSI model with 4 layers that powers the internet:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Application Layer</strong> - User services and applications</li>
            <li><strong>Transport Layer</strong> - End-to-end communication (TCP/UDP)</li>
            <li><strong>Internet Layer</strong> - Routing between networks (IP)</li>
            <li><strong>Link Layer</strong> - Physical connections and hardware</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Understanding how TCP/IP works is crucial as it's the foundation of all internet communications.
          </p>
          <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/learning/ddos/glossary/tcp-ip/" class="learn-btn" target="_blank">Learn More</a>
        </div>
        
        <div class="tech-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-project-diagram"></i> Network Types</h3>
          <p>Networks come in different sizes and purposes:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>LAN (Local Area Network)</strong> - Small network in a single location</li>
            <li><strong>WAN (Wide Area Network)</strong> - Connects LANs across distances</li>
            <li><strong>MAN (Metropolitan Area Network)</strong> - City-sized network</li>
            <li><strong>PAN (Personal Area Network)</strong> - Very small network (Bluetooth)</li>
            <li><strong>WLAN (Wireless LAN)</strong> - Wireless local network (Wi-Fi)</li>
          </ul>
          <a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/solutions/enterprise-networks/what-is-a-lan-local-area-network.html" class="learn-btn" target="_blank">Learn More</a>
        </div>
        
        <div class="tech-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-sitemap"></i> Network Topologies</h3>
          <p>
            Network topology refers to the physical or logical layout of devices:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Star</strong> - Devices connect to a central hub/switch</li>
            <li><strong>Bus</strong> - All devices connect to a single backbone</li>
            <li><strong>Ring</strong> - Devices form a closed loop</li>
            <li><strong>Mesh</strong> - Devices connect to multiple other devices</li>
            <li><strong>Hybrid</strong> - Combination of different topologies</li>
          </ul>
          <p>Each topology has advantages and disadvantages in terms of cost, reliability, and scalability.</p>
          <a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/solutions/enterprise-networks/what-is-network-topology.html" class="learn-btn" target="_blank">Learn More</a>
        </div>
        
        <div class="tech-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-map-marker-alt"></i> IP Addressing</h3>
          <p>
            IP addresses uniquely identify devices on a network:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>IPv4</strong> - 32-bit addresses (e.g., 192.168.1.1)</li>
            <li><strong>IPv6</strong> - 128-bit addresses for more devices</li>
            <li><strong>Public vs Private</strong> - Internet vs local network addresses</li>
            <li><strong>Subnetting</strong> - Dividing networks into smaller networks</li>
            <li><strong>CIDR Notation</strong> - Representing IP ranges (192.168.1.0/24)</li>
          </ul>
          <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/learning/network-layer/what-is-an-ip-address/" class="learn-btn" target="_blank">Learn More</a>
        </div>
        
        <div class="tech-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-wifi"></i> Wireless Networking</h3>
          <p>
            Wireless networks connect devices without physical cables:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Wi-Fi Standards</strong> - 802.11a/b/g/n/ac/ax (Wi-Fi 6)</li>
            <li><strong>Frequencies</strong> - 2.4GHz vs 5GHz bands</li>
            <li><strong>Security</strong> - WEP, WPA, WPA2, WPA3</li>
            <li><strong>Channels</strong> - Avoiding interference</li>
            <li><strong>Range and Signal Strength</strong> - Factors affecting performance</li>
          </ul>
          <a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/solutions/enterprise-networks/what-is-wifi.html" class="learn-btn" target="_blank">Learn More</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  
    <section id="protocols">
      <h2 class="section-title">Essential Protocols</h2>
      <p class="intro-text">
        Protocols are the languages that devices use to communicate. Understanding these protocols is crucial for 
        troubleshooting network issues and designing efficient systems.
      </p>
      
      <div class="tech-grid">
        <div class="tech-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-route"></i> Routing Protocols</h3>
          <p>
            Routing protocols determine the best path for data to travel across networks:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>OSPF (Open Shortest Path First)</strong> - Interior gateway protocol using link-state algorithm</li>
            <li><strong>BGP (Border Gateway Protocol)</strong> - Exterior gateway protocol that routes between autonomous systems</li>
            <li><strong>RIP (Routing Information Protocol)</strong> - Simple distance-vector protocol</li>
            <li><strong>EIGRP (Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol)</strong> - Cisco's advanced routing protocol</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            <strong>For beginners:</strong> Start with understanding the difference between static and dynamic routing before diving into specific protocols.
          </p>
          <a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/solutions/enterprise-networks/what-is-routing.html" class="learn-btn" target="_blank">Learn More</a>
        </div>
        
        <div class="tech-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-globe"></i> Application Protocols</h3>
          <p>
            These protocols enable specific applications and services:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>HTTP/HTTPS</strong> - Web browsing (port 80/443)</li>
            <li><strong>FTP</strong> - File transfers (port 21)</li>
            <li><strong>SMTP/POP3/IMAP</strong> - Email (ports 25, 110, 143)</li>
            <li><strong>SSH</strong> - Secure remote access (port 22)</li>
            <li><strong>DNS</strong> - Domain name resolution (port 53)</li>
            <li><strong>DHCP</strong> - Automatic IP assignment (ports 67/68)</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            <strong>Beginner tip:</strong> Learn common port numbers and what each protocol does in simple terms.
          </p>
          <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/learning/network-layer/what-is-a-protocol/" class="learn-btn" target="_blank">Learn More</a>
        </div>
        
        <div class="tech-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-exchange-alt"></i> Transport Protocols</h3>
          <p>
            Transport protocols manage the delivery of data between devices:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>TCP (Transmission Control Protocol)</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Connection-oriented and reliable</li>
                <li>Three-way handshake (SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK)</li>
                <li>Error checking and retransmission</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>UDP (User Datagram Protocol)</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Connectionless and faster</li>
                <li>No error recovery</li>
                <li>Used for streaming, gaming, DNS</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            <strong>For beginners:</strong> Think of TCP as a phone call (confirmed connection) and UDP as sending a letter (no confirmation).
          </p>
          <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/learning/ddos/glossary/tcp-ip/" class="learn-btn" target="_blank">Learn More</a>
        </div>
        
        <div class="tech-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-server"></i> Network Services</h3>
          <p>
            These services provide essential functionality for networks:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>DNS (Domain Name System)</strong> - Translates domain names to IP addresses</li>
            <li><strong>DHCP (Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol)</strong> - Automatically assigns IP addresses</li>
            <li><strong>NAT (Network Address Translation)</strong> - Allows multiple devices to share one public IP</li>
            <li><strong>Proxy Servers</strong> - Intermediaries for requests between clients and servers</li>
            <li><strong>Load Balancers</strong> - Distribute traffic across multiple servers</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            <strong>Beginner exercise:</strong> Try to explain how DNS works when you type a website address in your browser.
          </p>
          <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/learning/dns/what-is-dns/" class="learn-btn" target="_blank">Learn More</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  
    <section id="security">
      <h2 class="section-title">Network Security</h2>
      <p class="intro-text">
        Security is a critical aspect of networking. Understanding how to protect networks from threats is essential 
        for any networking professional.
      </p>
      
      <div class="tech-grid">
        <div class="tech-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-shield-alt"></i> Firewalls</h3>
          <p>
            Firewalls monitor and control incoming and outgoing network traffic:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Packet Filtering</strong> - Examines packets based on rules</li>
            <li><strong>Stateful Inspection</strong> - Tracks active connections</li>
            <li><strong>Application Layer</strong> - Analyzes specific application data</li>
            <li><strong>Next-Generation Firewalls</strong> - Combines traditional firewall with advanced features</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            <strong>For beginners:</strong> Think of a firewall as a security guard that checks IDs before allowing entry.
          </p>
          <a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/firewalls/what-is-a-firewall.html" class="learn-btn" target="_blank">Learn More</a>
        </div>
        
        <div class="tech-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-lock"></i> Encryption</h3>
          <p>
            Encryption protects data by converting it into a code that only authorized parties can read:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Symmetric Encryption</strong> - Same key for encryption and decryption</li>
            <li><strong>Asymmetric Encryption</strong> - Public and private key pairs</li>
            <li><strong>TLS/SSL</strong> - Secures web traffic (HTTPS)</li>
            <li><strong>VPN</strong> - Creates encrypted tunnels for private communication</li>
            <li><strong>IPsec</strong> - Security protocol for IP communications</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            <strong>Beginner tip:</strong> Look for the padlock icon in your browser to ensure a website uses encryption.
          </p>
          <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/learning/ssl/what-is-encryption/" class="learn-btn" target="_blank">Learn More</a>
        </div>
        
        <div class="tech-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-user-shield"></i> Authentication & Authorization</h3>
          <p>
            Verifying identity and controlling access to network resources:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Authentication Protocols</strong> - RADIUS, TACACS+, Kerberos</li>
            <li><strong>Multi-Factor Authentication</strong> - Something you know, have, and are</li>
            <li><strong>Access Control Lists (ACLs)</strong> - Rules that filter traffic</li>
            <li><strong>Role-Based Access Control</strong> - Permissions based on user roles</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            <strong>For beginners:</strong> Authentication answers "Who are you?" while authorization answers "What are you allowed to do?"
          </p>
          <a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/identity-services-engine/what-is-network-access-control.html" class="learn-btn" target="_blank">Learn More</a>
        </div>
        
        <div class="tech-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-radar"></i> IDS/IPS</h3>
          <p>
            Systems that monitor and respond to suspicious network activity:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>IDS (Intrusion Detection System)</strong> - Monitors and alerts on suspicious activity</li>
            <li><strong>IPS (Intrusion Prevention System)</strong> - Actively blocks detected threats</li>
            <li><strong>Signature-Based Detection</strong> - Matches known attack patterns</li>
            <li><strong>Anomaly-Based Detection</strong> - Identifies unusual behavior</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            <strong>Simple explanation:</strong> IDS is like a security camera that alerts you to intruders, while IPS is like a security guard that stops them.
          </p>
          <a href="https://www.paloaltonetworks.com/cyberpedia/what-is-an-ids-ips" class="learn-btn" target="_blank">Learn More</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
    
